ce:section.ce:para:
Because of the variability of Hg and the complexity of soil conditions, remediation of Hg-contaminated farmlands is still a huge challenge as a whole. For instance, rice paddies are considered the hot spots for Hg transformation and accumulation due to their complex soil conditions, such as the alternate aerobic and anaerobic conditions, abundant DOM and microbe communities, and the richness in many trace elements which facilitate the Hg transformation, release, and deposition (Amin et al., 2021; Wang et al., 2021). Therefore, apart from aquatic products, rice has been demonstrated to be another important global dietary source of human Hg, especially MeHg exposure (Liu et al., 2019). Rice MeHg exposure to humans is estimated to be approximately 9.9% of global MeHg exposure in 2013, and the exposure trend is continuously aggravated in Africa, Central Asia, and Europe (Liu et al., 2019). Meanwhile, researches have been ongoing to develop effective remediation technologies to restore the Hg-contaminated soils, including soil replacement, soil isolation, electrodynamic remediation, plant extraction, plant stabilization, chemical fixation, and soil washing (Li et al., 2019; O'Connor et al., 2018; Khalid et al., 2017). Recently, the application of some nanomaterials has been considered as the emerging green Hg remediation technology in preference to traditional remediation techniques (summarized and compared in Table 3
                     ). The achievable efficiencies for many nanomaterials are also considerable and displayed in Fig. 1
                     . The advantages of conventional methods, such as biochar, sulfide, and chloride reagents, used in Hg-polluted soil remediation mainly cover the acceptable efficiency and easy to be prepared. However, the addition of these chemical reagents may cause a substantial change of soil chemical properties and destroy soil biological and physical structures. The thermal desorption method is highly effective, but to be soil destroyed, expensive, and large instruments dependent, which limit its application in field Hg remediation. Nanotechnology-based methods applied in site Hg remediation in contaminated soils are attracting more and more attention worldwide because of their high efficiency, high reactivity, low cost, low toxicity, environmentally friendly feature, and easy to be treated after the remediation.
